üêç Python Lists

1. Introduction to Python Lists

Definition of a list

Representation using square brackets []
Ability to store multiple data types
Mutability of lists


3. List Built-in Functions

Categorize into:
  Addition methods: append(), extend(), insert()
  Deletion methods: pop(), remove(), clear()
  Other common operations: index(), count(), sort(), reverse(), copy()

üìå Python List Built-in Functions ‚Äì Examples

1Ô∏è‚É£ append()
      Adds one element at the end of the list.
Example:
a = [10, 20, 30]
a.append(40)
print(a)
Output:
[10, 20, 30, 40]

2Ô∏è‚É£ extend()
      Adds multiple elements to the list.
Example:
a = [10, 20]
a.extend([30, 40])
print(a)
Output:
[10, 20, 30, 40]

3Ô∏è‚É£ insert()
      Adds an element at a specific index.
Example:
a = [10, 30, 40]
a.insert(1, 20)
print(a)
Output:
[10, 20, 30, 40]

4Ô∏è‚É£ pop()
    Removes and returns the last element.
Example:
a = [10, 20, 30]
a.pop()
print(a)
Output:
[10, 20]

5Ô∏è‚É£ remove()
      Removes a specific value from the list.
Example:
a = [10, 20, 30]
a.remove(20)
print(a)
Output:
[10, 30]

6Ô∏è‚É£ sort()
    Sorts the list in ascending order.
Example:
a = [40, 10, 30, 20]
a.sort()
print(a)
Output:
[10, 20, 30, 40]

7Ô∏è‚É£ reverse()
      Reverses the order of the list.
Example:
a = [1, 2, 3]
a.reverse()
print(a)
Output:
[3, 2, 1]

8Ô∏è‚É£ clear()
      Removes all elements from the list.
Example:
a = [10, 20, 30]
a.clear()
print(a)
Output:
[]

9Ô∏è‚É£ copy()
    Creates a shallow copy of the list.
Example:
a = [10, 20, 30]
b = a.copy()
print(b)
Output:
[10, 20, 30]





